 gentrification, with a focus on the history and theory of community in urban policy. Engaging with debates as to how urban policy has changed, and continues to change, following the financial crash of 2008, the book provides an essential antidote to those who claim that culture and society can replicate the role of the state. Based on research from the UK Arts and Humanities Research Council’s Connected Communities programme and with a unique set of case studies drawing on artistic and cultural community work, the book will appeal to scholars and students in geography, urban studies, planning, sociology, law and art as well as policy makers and community workers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aUrban renewal. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aAncarno, Clyde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnelly, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurose, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarte, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Phil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhan, Amadu Wurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLayard, Antonia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorne, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator